{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>This entry consists of antitermination proteins found in bacteriophages, such as protein Q from phage lambda, and some bacterial homologues. Protein Q positively regulates expression of the phage late gene operon by binding to the bacterial host RNA polymerase (RNAP) and modifying it. This protein binds a specific DNA Q-binding element (QBE) and interacts with RNAP. The modified RNAP can read without pausing and through transcription terminators preceding late genes [[cite:PUB00034461], [cite:PUB00097869]]. It participates in the lysis-lysogeny decision by activating the expression of the late lytic genes [[cite:PUB00097868]]. The structure of Q from bacteriophage 21 revealed that it forms a torus, that narrows and extends the RNAP RNA-exit channel and extrudes the linked RNA, preventing the formation of pause and terminator hairpins [[cite:PUB00097869]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "7ubj", "name" "Transcription antitermination factor Qlambda, type-I crystal"}, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR038500", "name" "Antitermination protein Q superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"hamap" {"MF_04158" "Antitermination protein Q [Q]"}, "pfam" {"PF03589" "Antitermination protein"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Antitermination protein Q", "short" "Antitermntn"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 6, "domain_architectures" 3, "proteomes" 148, "taxa" 1074, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 2304, "sets" 0, "proteins" 2253, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 1667}, "pathways" 0}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {}, :set-info nil, :accession "IPR003222", :literature {"PUB00034461" {"URL" nil, "issue" "11", "authors" ["Guo J" "Roberts JW."], "ISO_journal" "J. Bacteriol.", "DOI_URL" "http://dx.doi.org/10.1128/JB.186.11.3599-3608.2004", "medline_journal" "J Ba